00:35:22,662 --> 00:35:26,098
God Jake, I can’t be without you, I love you!

520
00:35:30,088 --> 00:35:31,141
You’re meant for better.

521
00:35:31,208 --> 00:35:32,517
- I’m not! 
- You are.

522
00:35:33,194 --> 00:35:36,758
Hey, look, I don’t know, maybe I’ll find Jenny sooner than later. Maybe I’ll be back-

523
00:35:36,828 --> 00:35:38,979
You won't! You know you won’t!

524
00:35:40,702 --> 00:35:41,638
Come here.

525
00:35:44,575 --> 00:35:45,579
Listen to me.

526
00:35:47,130 --> 00:35:48,253
I need you...

527
00:35:49,793 --> 00:35:51,391
- to get past this. 
- No!

528
00:35:51,477 --> 00:35:54,237
I need you to forget about me and move on.

529
00:35:55,226 --> 00:35:56,009
Okay?

530
00:35:57,396 --> 00:35:59,449
You’re too amazing to carry this around.

531
00:35:59,870 --> 00:36:01,800
You’re too full of greatness and...

532
00:36:05,102 --> 00:36:06,705
I love you too much.

533
00:36:13,177 --> 00:36:14,109
But I have to go.

534
00:36:14,212 --> 00:36:15,019
No!

535
00:36:17,272 --> 00:36:19,146
You know, I can’t have Jenny be with Nikki.

536
00:36:34,222 --> 00:36:35,178
Jake!

537
00:36:41,548 --> 00:36:42,556
Thank you.

538
00:36:45,645 --> 00:36:47,865
You know, I coulda held you in my arms forever.

539
00:36:50,594 --> 00:36:52,714
It still wouldn’t have been long enough.

540
00:38:04,860 --> 00:38:06,637
You miss Haley, don’t you?

541
00:38:10,541 --> 00:38:11,794
You gonna be alright?

542
00:38:14,548 --> 00:38:16,851
Yeah, it’s just hard to let someone go, you know?

543
00:38:21,402 --> 00:38:23,297
It’s okay that you’re into Peyton.

544
00:38:25,723 --> 00:38:29,477
I’ve been avoiding it the whole trip, but I found the things in your closet;

545
00:38:29,774 --> 00:38:30,721
and its fine.

546
00:39:04,505 --> 00:39:06,613
I just wanted to say goodbye before I left.

547
00:39:06,931 --> 00:39:09,343
You’re leaving now? Tonight?

548
00:39:10,166 --> 00:39:11,401
I think it’s best.

549
00:39:12,373 --> 00:39:13,300
For mum...

550
00:39:14,744 --> 00:39:15,753
and for you.

551
00:39:22,516 --> 00:39:24,098
Andy...

552
00:39:29,817 --> 00:39:32,711
Oh, and... I need you to give this to Lucas.

553
00:39:33,637 --> 00:39:34,410
Of course.

554
00:39:46,908 --> 00:39:47,717
Andy.

555
00:39:51,362 --> 00:39:52,734
I love you, you know?

556
00:39:56,356 --> 00:39:57,481
I do.

557
00:39:58,116 --> 00:39:59,346
And I love you, Karen.

558
00:40:03,399 --> 00:40:06,056
But, somehow, it just... doesn’t seem to be enough.

559
00:40:25,408 --> 00:40:27,571
George Bernard Shaw once wrote:

560
00:40:28,131 --> 00:40:30,126
‘There are two tragedies in life:

561
00:40:30,700 --> 00:40:32,784
one is to lose your heart’s desire...

562
00:40:33,711 --> 00:40:35,549
the other is to gain it’.

563
00:40:36,793 --> 00:40:39,604
Clearly, Shaw had his heart broken once or twice.

564
00:40:54,311 --> 00:40:55,327
Where you been?

565
00:40:56,337 --> 00:40:57,452
Went to see a friend.

566
00:40:57,796 --> 00:40:59,920
Yeah? Anyone I know?

567
00:41:03,975 --> 00:41:04,989
Not really.

568
00:41:07,390 --> 00:41:08,838
You know you’re bleeding?

569
00:41:09,441 --> 00:41:10,686
Yeah.

570
00:41:12,024 --> 00:41:13,478
It should probably hurt, but...

571
00:41:14,093 --> 00:41:16,469
it’s kinda weird; I don’t feel anything.

572
00:41:19,449 --> 00:41:21,589
As far as I’m concerned, Shaw was a punk.

573
00:41:22,075 --> 00:41:24,572
Coz you know what? Tragedies happen.

574
00:41:25,581 --> 00:41:28,818
What’re you gonna do, give up? Quit? No.

575
00:41:30,194 --> 00:41:35,049
I realise now that when your heart breaks, you gotta fight like hell to make sure you’re still alive.

576
00:41:36,339 --> 00:41:37,343
Coz you are,

577
00:41:37,736 --> 00:41:39,017
and that pain you feel...

578
00:41:39,647 --> 00:41:40,655
it’s life.

579
00:41:41,173 --> 00:41:42,678
The confusion and fear...

580
00:41:43,486 --> 00:41:46,625
that’s there to remind you that somewhere out there is something better.

581
00:41:47,730 --> 00:41:49,861
And that something is worth fighting for.

582
00:42:01,505 --> 00:42:05,007
This year, I got everything I wanted and everything I wished for...

583
00:42:05,631 --> 00:42:09,358
but, in a way, I lost even more.

584
00:42:09,614 --> 00:42:11,843
Haley, the new tour posters are here.

585
00:42:14,068 --> 00:42:14,857
What’s this?

586
00:42:15,138 --> 00:42:19,322
Um... nothing, you know, just... stupid kid stuff.

587
00:42:21,713 --> 00:42:22,522
What d’ya think?

588
00:42:22,712 --> 00:42:23,556
Wow!

589
00:42:30,145 --> 00:42:31,395
Shaw was right:

590
00:42:31,897 --> 00:42:34,553
as we strain to grasp the things we desire...

591
00:42:34,672 --> 00:42:37,150
the things we think will make our lives better...

592
00:42:37,442 --> 00:42:40,406
money, popularity, fame...

593
00:42:40,693 --> 00:42:42,719
we ignore what truly matters...

594
00:42:42,828 --> 00:42:49,064
the simple things: like friendship, family, love.

595
00:42:50,195 --> 00:42:52,612
The things we probably already had.

596
00:42:54,588 --> 00:42:58,163
So, Mr. Shaw thinks that getting your hearts desire is a tragedy?

597
00:42:59,437 --> 00:43:00,926
I say he’s wrong.

598
00:43:01,459 --> 00:43:05,045
I mean, clearly, Shaw never kissed Erica Marsh.

599
00:43:27,040 --> 00:43:29,784
Yes, losing your heart’s desire is tragic.

600
00:43:31,376 --> 00:43:33,106
But gaining your heart’s desire...

601
00:43:34,460 --> 00:43:35,866
it’s all you can hope for.

602
00:43:38,995 --> 00:43:40,976
This year, I wished for love.

603
00:43:42,973 --> 00:43:47,202
To immerse myself in someone else and to wake a heart long afraid to feel.

604
00:43:51,995 --> 00:43:53,597
My wish was granted.

605
00:43:56,567 --> 00:44:00,064
And if having that is tragic... then give me tragedy.

606
00:44:06,368 --> 00:44:08,946
Because, I wouldn’t give it back for the world.

607
00:44:42,110 --> 00:44:42,956
Hey.

608
00:44:45,462 --> 00:44:46,315
Need some help?

609
00:44:46,618 --> 00:44:47,298
Nah.

610
00:44:47,713 --> 00:44:51,379
I figure if I leave all my stuff here, my parents are gonna have to let me come back for senior year.

611
00:44:53,673 --> 00:44:56,258
Look, are we ever… gonna talk about Peyton?

612
00:44:56,846 --> 00:44:58,127
And the stuff you found?

613
00:44:58,548 --> 00:45:02,647
It’s not a big deal. Actually, I was… kinda relieved.

614
00:45:04,435 --> 00:45:05,480
Relieved?

615
00:45:05,818 --> 00:45:07,293
I thought you might be into me.

616
00:45:07,738 --> 00:45:12,653
And… that would’ve ruined everything because we’ve become friends…

617
00:45:12,735 --> 00:45:14,374
and that’s exactly what I needed.

618
00:45:14,737 --> 00:45:16,918
And… it’s exactly what I want.

619
00:45:18,253 --> 00:45:22,616
But you seemed… upset… that I held onto all that stuff; you still do.

620
00:45:24,040 --> 00:45:26,324
Finding that stuff was kind of like…

621
00:45:27,611 --> 00:45:28,628
evidence.

622
00:45:29,535 --> 00:45:32,699
Reminded me of what happened… and how it happened.

623
00:45:34,490 --> 00:45:36,727
And I guess my heart just wasn’t ready for that.

624
00:45:49,765 --> 00:45:51,428
How you feeling, Ms. Scott?

625
00:45:52,079 --> 00:45:54,495
Coach! How you doing?

626
00:45:55,555 --> 00:45:57,609
Well, I guess you’re waiting for Danny.

627
00:45:57,774 --> 00:46:00,322
Uh, yeah, yeah, he… planned to pick me up.

628
00:46:00,747 --> 00:46:02,763
I was… hoping he’d bring Nathan.

629
00:46:03,958 --> 00:46:05,238
I lied.

630
00:46:05,753 --> 00:46:08,836
I had one of the girls at the office put you back an hour.

631
00:46:09,302 --> 00:46:12,154
I thought you and I might… have a talk.

632
00:46:17,842 --> 00:46:19,635
Any chance you could tap that thing?

633
00:46:20,228 --> 00:46:21,754
Sorry, we’re closed.

634
00:46:22,533 --> 00:46:25,640
Well, I hope so because if this is open, you’ve got problems.

635
00:46:26,168 --> 00:46:27,381
Where’re you taking this?

636
00:46:27,914 --> 00:46:29,895
- Over there, but… 
- I got it.

637
00:46:30,386 --> 00:46:31,876
Uh… thanks.

638
00:46:31,953 --> 00:46:33,059
No problem.

639
00:46:33,607 --> 00:46:35,707
If I had a dollar for every keg I’ve carried,

640
00:46:36,249 --> 00:46:37,729
I’d be a rich girl.

641
00:46:38,493 --> 00:46:39,686
Bartender?

642
00:46:40,028 --> 00:46:42,701
Only when I’m not killing people or saving the world.

643
00:46:43,294 --> 00:46:46,648
Well, if you’re looking for a job, I can put in a good word with the owner.

644
00:46:46,760 --> 00:46:48,865
Actually, I’m looking for Peyton.

645
00:46:49,468 --> 00:46:50,611
Oh, um…

646
00:46:50,882 --> 00:46:52,044
I’m Peyton.

647
00:46:53,360 --> 00:46:56,176
Oh. I’m Ellie.

648
00:46:56,376 --> 00:46:58,966
I write a column for Alternative Press. You know it?

649
00:46:59,771 --> 00:47:01,844
Know it? I read it cover to cover.

650
00:47:02,049 --> 00:47:03,087
Which column?

651
00:47:03,447 --> 00:47:04,958
Actually, it’s a new one.

652
00:47:05,141 --> 00:47:09,651
But I heard some high school girl got The Wreckers and Jimmy Eat World to play her club night.

653
00:47:09,918 --> 00:47:12,170
And I wanted to know more. Whaddaya say?

654
00:47:12,607 --> 00:47:16,835
I’d say I’m really flattered, but… I think last night was my final show.

655
00:47:17,967 --> 00:47:20,225
Well, I assume there’s a reason for that?

656
00:47:21,572 --> 00:47:22,391
Yeah.

657
00:47:22,749 --> 00:47:24,941
Sounds like the makings of a great story.

658
00:47:25,729 --> 00:47:26,974
No thanks.

659
00:47:27,204 --> 00:47:28,990
But it was really nice to meet you.

660
00:47:30,005 --> 00:47:32,175
It’s nice to meet you too, Peyton.

661
00:47:48,453 --> 00:47:51,990
Luke, find the combination and Dan is… finished.

662
00:48:38,578 --> 00:48:39,326
Hey.

663
00:48:40,840 --> 00:48:41,722
What’s up?

664
00:48:42,463 --> 00:48:43,419
Nothing, you?

665
00:48:44,875 --> 00:48:46,681
I thought you said you were done spying on him.

666
00:48:47,685 --> 00:48:48,812
I am.

667
00:48:49,635 --> 00:48:50,716
Then what’s in the bag?

668
00:48:56,027 --> 00:48:58,469
Just… bringing this back to you.

669
00:48:59,543 --> 00:49:01,028
You gave me your word, Luke.

670
00:49:01,791 --> 00:49:04,212
I know, and I’m done.

671
00:49:05,878 --> 00:49:06,815
I promise.

672
00:49:26,067 --> 00:49:27,535
Giving up on your dreams?

673
00:49:28,734 --> 00:49:29,506
Mom.

674
00:49:29,654 --> 00:49:31,022
Oh, my boy.

675
00:49:32,307 --> 00:49:34,344
I have missed you.

676
00:49:35,845 --> 00:49:37,449
It’s gonna be okay now, mom.

677
00:49:37,708 --> 00:49:38,539
Yeah.

678
00:49:39,966 --> 00:49:41,933
So, what’s all this about?

679
00:49:43,023 --> 00:49:44,651
Nathan’s moving home, Deb.

680
00:49:48,831 --> 00:49:50,334
We’re gonna be a family again.

681
00:49:53,687 --> 00:49:54,845
Welcome home.

682
00:50:28,413 --> 00:50:30,302
- Hi-O! 
- Oh God!

683
00:50:31,588 --> 00:50:32,442
What?

684
00:50:33,383 --> 00:50:34,832
You scared the hell outta me.

685
00:50:35,810 --> 00:50:38,713
You don’t know anybody who has IM named ‘WATCHMEWATCHU’, do you?

686
00:50:38,827 --> 00:50:42,354
Hmm... sounds pervy. Sadly no, why?

687
00:50:43,133 --> 00:50:45,487
Doesn’t matter. Sup?

688
00:50:45,581 --> 00:50:47,381
It’s actually what I came to ask you.

689
00:50:47,531 --> 00:50:51,754
Couldn’t find you at the club last night; figured maybe you stayed in with Jake.

690
00:50:51,827 --> 00:50:53,527
Jake’s gone, Brooke.

691
00:50:55,447 --> 00:50:56,862
Nikki has Jenny.

692
00:50:57,736 --> 00:51:00,361
Oh, Peyton, come here. What happened?

693
00:51:02,707 --> 00:51:07,458
I can’t, coz if you hug me, then I’m gonna start… bawling again, so…

694
00:51:09,051 --> 00:51:10,877
some summer break, huh?

695
00:51:12,993 --> 00:51:15,389
Well… I mean, he’s coming back, right?

696
00:51:15,486 --> 00:51:18,958
He’ll… find Jenny and then he can slap Nikki

697
00:51:19,034 --> 00:51:22,270
and then he’s coming right back to you! I just know it.

698
00:51:22,649 --> 00:51:23,586
Thanks.

699
00:51:25,183 --> 00:51:28,103
Okay, I’m sorry, I’m changing the subject;

700
00:51:28,178 --> 00:51:31,424
how was your road trip with Lucas.

701
00:51:31,528 --> 00:51:34,283
Um… fine.

702
00:51:34,419 --> 00:51:37,266
Fine? Is this gonna get sexual?

703
00:51:38,598 --> 00:51:40,653
I don’t know, that’s kind of up to you.

704
00:51:40,841 --> 00:51:41,593
What?

705
00:51:42,577 --> 00:51:45,397
It can wait. You’re head is spinning.

706
00:51:46,498 --> 00:51:50,128
Brooke, considering you’re leaving, tomorrow, it can’t wait.

707
00:51:50,722 --> 00:51:51,644
Spill!

708
00:51:52,112 --> 00:51:53,016
Okay.

709
00:51:54,710 --> 00:51:58,310
Um… I was snooping through Lucas’ things; kind of on purpose,

710
00:51:58,356 --> 00:52:01,448
and found a bunch of your stuff that he saved and I think he’s still into you.

711
00:52:03,803 --> 00:52:08,668
Like I said: bad timing… seeing that Jake just left, or maybe good timing?

712
00:52:10,097 --> 00:52:13,163
Brooke, I’m sorry.

713
00:52:13,491 --> 00:52:15,652
I know you have feelings for Lucas.

714
00:52:16,348 --> 00:52:17,869
Phantom feelings.

715
00:52:17,992 --> 00:52:20,986
Like… when you lose a leg and try to scratch it.

716
00:52:21,437 --> 00:52:25,657
Lucas was my… gangrene infected, amputated limb.

717
00:52:25,979 --> 00:52:26,870
Really?

718
00:52:28,585 --> 00:52:31,410
I was so insecure when I was with him, Peyton…

719
00:52:31,600 --> 00:52:35,630
and this whole thing just reminded me that I don’t wanna be that girl again.

720
00:52:36,373 --> 00:52:37,401
I won’t be.

721
00:52:40,550 --> 00:52:43,444
Marcus, I don’t understand, he was supposed to be there by now.

722
00:52:44,426 --> 00:52:47,672
Well… can you leave him another message in case he checks in?

723
00:52:48,010 --> 00:52:49,173
Andy Hargrove.

724
00:52:49,776 --> 00:52:50,616
Thanks.

725
00:53:08,711 --> 00:53:09,586
Karen?

726
00:53:10,369 --> 00:53:11,870
Oh my gosh, Deb!

727
00:53:13,147 --> 00:53:14,214
Welcome back!

728
00:53:15,070 --> 00:53:17,107
You look like you just saw a ghost.

729
00:53:17,506 --> 00:53:18,894
Well, I think I did.

730
00:53:19,508 --> 00:53:20,604
How you feeling?

731
00:53:20,691 --> 00:53:25,253
Uh, good. Great actually. I just… I need to keep busy.

732
00:53:25,357 --> 00:53:28,351
Are you sure? I mean… you don’t wanna take some time?

733
00:53:28,433 --> 00:53:30,066
Uh, no, no, absolutely not.

734
00:53:30,143 --> 00:53:32,206
Well, okay. Let’s talk.

735
00:53:32,278 --> 00:53:33,133
Okay.

736
00:53:40,833 --> 00:53:42,703
You’re not going away, are you?

737
00:53:44,166 --> 00:53:45,334
Not this time.

738
00:53:46,650 --> 00:53:48,017
That’s a rad jacket.

739
00:53:48,385 --> 00:53:49,291
Thanks.

740
00:53:49,799 --> 00:53:51,555
I stole it from Courtney Love.

741
00:53:51,847 --> 00:53:52,553
Really?

742
00:53:52,640 --> 00:53:55,037
Yeah. She was being a bitch.

743
00:53:55,149 --> 00:53:56,173
So I took it.

744
00:53:57,484 --> 00:53:58,400
Have a seat.

745
00:53:59,559 --> 00:54:05,370
So, the editors at THUD are thrilled about your story and they say I have to talk to you.

746
00:54:06,172 --> 00:54:07,554
Is it that bad?

747
00:54:07,781 --> 00:54:11,257
Well, if there’s no House of Freaks at TRIC, there’s no story.

748
00:54:12,471 --> 00:54:15,487
And what about the rest of your life? Is it that bad?

749
00:54:17,201 --> 00:54:18,650
What do you know about it?

750
00:54:20,000 --> 00:54:25,573
Well… your eyes are puffy which, from experience, screams textbook crying eyes.

751
00:54:25,665 --> 00:54:30,181
You have your hair up so you’re probably not planning on impressing any boys today.

752
00:54:30,246 --> 00:54:35,209
I’d say you’re nursing a hell of a broken heart; and not the school-girl crush kind, the real thing.

753
00:54:38,015 --> 00:54:40,350
Um… okay.

754
00:54:40,433 --> 00:54:44,762
Uh… well, I mean, I started TRIC to escape it all, you know, and…

755
00:54:44,854 --> 00:54:48,255
bring people together; let the music drown out the white noise in life.

756
00:54:48,341 --> 00:54:49,940
And tell me about your life.

757
00:54:50,133 --> 00:54:51,961
What is the white noise made of?

758
00:54:52,049 --> 00:54:55,187
Oh, god, I mean… everything unnecessary…

759
00:54:55,269 --> 00:55:00,620
like… cliques and… greed and popularity and harassment-

760
00:55:00,707 --> 00:55:02,330
The song remains the same.

761
00:55:02,412 --> 00:55:04,138
Yeah, as far as I can tell, it does.

762
00:55:10,057 --> 00:55:11,787
Looks like we’re both getting better.

763
00:55:12,790 --> 00:55:14,516
You love this game, don’t you?

764
00:55:15,500 --> 00:55:17,107
Depends on what day you ask me.

765
00:55:17,521 --> 00:55:20,332
Nah, you loved it every day since you could hold a ball.

766
00:55:21,551 --> 00:55:23,962
So… why aren’t you going to the camp?

767
00:55:24,925 --> 00:55:26,143
You talk to dad?

768
00:55:26,585 --> 00:55:27,710
Talked to Whitey.

769
00:55:28,269 --> 00:55:30,674
He said you’re staying because of me.

770
00:55:31,095 --> 00:55:32,892
Whitey also drinks a lot, mom.

771
00:55:34,638 --> 00:55:35,652
Then you’ll go.

772
00:55:38,083 --> 00:55:39,169
Look, uh…

773
00:55:40,879 --> 00:55:42,588
dad told me about the pills;

774
00:55:42,922 --> 00:55:44,863
about how you started taking them because…

775
00:55:44,939 --> 00:55:46,131
Because what?

776
00:55:46,931 --> 00:55:48,118
Because I moved out.

777
